

============================
ON-PREMISES : What is On-Premises?
============================

On-premises means:
You own and manage everything yourself (your own datacenter) 

This includes:
- Servers (big computers)
- Storage
- Networking equipment
- Power
- Cooling
- Security
- IT staff to maintain it


============================
CLOUD : What is Cloud?
============================

Cloud means:
Using someone else’s computers (servers) over the internet
instead of owning and managing your own.


============================
EXAMPLE: Running a Website
============================

ON-PREMISES:

- Buy a server
- Install OS and software
- Set up networking
- Handle power & cooling
- Fix hardware issues
- Upgrade when traffic grows
- Limited storage - External hard drive or  server
- Limited space
- If it breaks → data loss risk

Result:
- Takes time
- High cost
- Requires expertise


CLOUD:

- Create an account
- Click "Create Server"
- Choose server size
- Pay per hour or usage
- Scale up or down anytime AS PER REQUIREMENT 

Result:
- Fast
- Flexible
- Beginner-friendly


============================
KEY BENEFITS OF CLOUD
(Why Cloud is Popular)
============================

- No hardware to buy
- Pay only for what you use (Ondemand )
- Easy to scale resources
- High availability
- High Scalability
- Faster to start
- Global access from anywhere


============================
WHEN ON-PREMISES IS STILL USED
============================

Some companies prefer on-premises when:

- Strict data security laws exist
- Internet is not reliable
- Legacy systems are in use
- Full control over systems is required


==================================================
AWS FREE TIER 


AWS Free Tier allows new users to try AWS services
without paying immediately.

It is mainly used for:
- Learning AWS
- Practice
- Small experiments
- Beginners in Cloud


========================================
AWS FREE TIER – CURRENT USAGE MODEL
(NEW ACCOUNTS)
========================================

For new AWS accounts:

- AWS offers a Free Plan with credits
- You can get up to $200 AWS credits
  - $100 at signup
  - Up to $100 by completing learning activities

- Valid for:
  - 6 months
  - OR until credits are used (whichever comes first)

- No charges unless you upgrade to Paid Plan


========================================
IS IT FREE FOR 1 YEAR OR 6 MONTHS?
========================================

- Older AWS accounts (created earlier):
  - Had 12 months Free Tier for many services

- New AWS accounts:
  - Mostly follow 6-month Free Plan with credits

Note:
- AWS model may change over time
- Always check usage limits in AWS console


========================================
ALWAYS FREE SERVICES
(NO EXPIRY – WITH LIMITS)
========================================

Some services are free every month
within certain limits, even after credits end.

Examples:
- AWS Lambda
  - 1 million free requests per month
- Amazon S3
  - Limited free storage
- Amazon DynamoDB
  - Free storage and read/write capacity

(Usage limits apply)


========================================
IMPORTANT POINTS TO REMEMBER
========================================

- Credit card is required to create AWS account ( Call your customer care) 
- AWS follows pay-as-you-use model
- If you exceed free limits → you will be charged
- Always monitor billing dashboard


