======================================================

    DIFFERENCE BETWEEN AWS REGION AND AVAILABILITY ZONE

    --------------------------------------------------
    AWS REGION
    --------------------------------------------------

        • A geographic location in the world.
        • Each region contains multiple data centers.
        • Regions are completely isolated from each other.
        • Used for:
              - Disaster recovery
              - Data residency requirements
              - Latency-based deployments

        Examples:
            us-east-1  (N. Virginia)
            ap-south-1 (Mumbai)
            eu-west-1  (Ireland)


    --------------------------------------------------
    AVAILABILITY ZONE (AZ)
    --------------------------------------------------

        • A physically separate data center *inside* a region.
        • Each region has 2–6+ AZs.
        • AZs are isolated but connected with low-latency networks.
        • Used for:
              - High availability
              - Fault tolerance
              - Redundant architecture

        Example inside ap-south-1 (Mumbai):
            ap-south-1a
            ap-south-1b
            ap-south-1c


    --------------------------------------------------
    SIMPLE DIFFERENCE
    --------------------------------------------------

        Region:
            A geographical area (big)

        Availability Zone:
            Data centers inside a region (smaller)


    --------------------------------------------------

        A region is a geographic location, while availability
        zones are isolated data centers within that region,
        designed for high availability and fault tolerance.


-------------------------------------------------
    WHY MULTI-AZ DEPLOYMENTS GIVE HIGH AVAILABILITY
    --------------------------------------------------

        Because when you deploy across multiple AZs:

            If AZ-A goes down,
            AZ-B automatically serves traffic.

        Example:
            • 2 EC2 instances in different AZs
            • ALB balances traffic
            • RDS Multi-AZ keeps standby replica
            • Auto Scaling replaces failed instances


    By default Availability Zones are not replicas of each other.
        They are independent data centers within a region.
        High availability is achieved when YOU deploy your
        application and data across multiple AZs.
		
		
		
		
