====================================================================================
TAGS:

    WHY TAGS ARE IMPORTANT IN AWS

    --------------------------------------------------
    OVERVIEW
    --------------------------------------------------

        Tags are key–value pairs attached to resources like EC2, S3, RDS,
        EBS, VPC, Load Balancers, and more.

        Example:
            Key: Name
            Value: Web-Server-01


    --------------------------------------------------
    WHY TAGS ARE NEEDED
    --------------------------------------------------

        Tags help in identifying, organizing, filtering,
        automating, and managing AWS resources at scale.


    --------------------------------------------------
    MAIN BENEFITS OF TAGGING
    --------------------------------------------------

        1) Identification
            - Helps you understand the purpose of a resource.
            - Example:
                  Name = Production-App-Server

        2) Cost Allocation
            - Track cloud expenses by project, team, or environment.
            - Example:
                  Project = Billing-App
                  Environment = Prod

        3) Automation
            - Scripts and tools use tags to target resources.
            - Example:
                  Shutdown = True
              → nightly automation shuts down tagged servers.

        4) Security and Compliance
            - IAM policies can allow or deny actions based on tags.
            - Example:
                  Owner = DevOps

        5) Monitoring and Alerts
            - CloudWatch filters alarms using tags.
            - Example:
                  Team = SRE

        6) Resource Organization
            - Easily search and filter resources.
            - Useful in large environments.

        7) Auto Scaling Integration
            - Auto Scaling Groups apply tags to new EC2 instances.


    --------------------------------------------------
    COMMON TAG EXAMPLES
    --------------------------------------------------

        Name=backend-server-01
        Environment=production
        Owner=DevOps
        Team=Cloud
        CostCenter=Finance
        Application=Ecommerce
        Backup=True


    --------------------------------------------------
    REAL DEVOPS USE CASES
    --------------------------------------------------

        - Stop all Development EC2 instances automatically at night
        - Take backups only for EBS volumes tagged Backup=True
        - Track monthly cost by team or project
        - Apply IAM governance using tags
        - Group CloudWatch logs or metrics by tag
        - Terraform uses tags to manage infrastructure cleanly


    --------------------------------------------------
    INTERVIEW ONE-LINER
    --------------------------------------------------

        Tags in AWS are key–value labels that help with identification,
        cost tracking, automation, security, and large-scale resource
        management.



========================================================================================================

4 FEB 2026:

    --------------------------------------------------
    WHAT IS A LOAD BALANCER?
    --------------------------------------------------

        A Load Balancer distributes incoming traffic across
        multiple servers (EC2 instances) to ensure:

            • High availability
            • Fault tolerance
            • Better performance
            • Zero downtime during failures

        Simple meaning:
            Instead of sending all traffic to one server,
            the load balancer spreads it across many.


    --------------------------------------------------
    TYPES OF LOAD BALANCERS IN AWS
    --------------------------------------------------

        there are 3 main load balancers:

        1) ALB – Application Load Balancer
        2) NLB – Network Load Balancer
        3) GWLB – Gateway Load Balancer
		4) Classic Load Balancer


    ==================================================
    1) APPLICATION LOAD BALANCER (ALB)
    ==================================================

        • Operates at Layer 7 (HTTP/HTTPS)
        • Understands content of HTTP requests
        • Used for web applications and microservices

        Supports:
            - Path-based routing      (/login → server1)
            - Host-based routing      (api.example.com)
            - Query/Headers routing
            - URL-based routing
            - WebSockets
            - TLS termination (HTTPS)
            - Redirects / fixed responses

        Best use cases:
            • Web apps
            • APIs / Microservices
            • Routing based on URL or domain


    ==================================================
    2) NETWORK LOAD BALANCER (NLB)
    ==================================================

        • Operates at Layer 4 (TCP/UDP)
        • Fastest and highest performance
        • Handles millions of requests/second
        • Used for low-latency, real-time traffic

        Supports:
            - TCP / UDP / TLS
            - Static IP
            - Cross-zone balancing
            - High network throughput

        Best use cases:
            • Gaming
            • Real-time apps
            • High-performance workloads
            • Load balancing non-HTTP traffic


    ==================================================
    3) GATEWAY LOAD BALANCER (GWLB)
    ==================================================

        • Operates at Layer 3 (Network Layer)
        • Used for security appliances

        Example appliances:
            - Firewalls
            - IDS / IPS systems
            - Packet inspection tools

        Best use cases:
            • Insert firewalls between VPCs
            • Centralizing traffic inspection


    --------------------------------------------------
    WHEN TO USE WHICH?
    --------------------------------------------------

        ALB → Websites, APIs, HTTP/HTTPS  
        NLB → High performance TCP/UDP  
        GWLB → Firewalls, deep packet inspection  


    ==================================================
    ALB – CONFIGURATION OPTIONS (IMPORTANT)
    ==================================================

    --------------------------------------------------
    1) Basic Configuration
    --------------------------------------------------

        • Name
        • Scheme:
              - Internet-facing
              - Internal
        • IP Address Type:
              - IPv4
              - Dualstack (IPv4 + IPv6)
        • VPC selection

    --------------------------------------------------
    2) Network Mapping
    --------------------------------------------------

        • Select subnets in multiple AZs
        • Enable/disable cross-zone load balancing

    --------------------------------------------------
    3) Listeners
    --------------------------------------------------

        Example listeners:
            • HTTP (80)
            • HTTPS (443)

        Each listener requires:
            - Rule(s)
            - Default target group

    --------------------------------------------------
    4) SSL Certificates (for HTTPS)
    --------------------------------------------------

        • ACM certificate
        • TLS version
        • Security policies

    --------------------------------------------------
    5) Routing Rules
    --------------------------------------------------

        You can create:

            • Path-based rules
                 /app1  → TG-App1
                 /app2  → TG-App2

            • Host-based rules
                 api.example.com → API-Target-Group

            • Header-based routing
            • Query-string routing
            • HTTP method filters
            • Redirect actions
            • Fixed responses

    --------------------------------------------------
    6) Security Settings
    --------------------------------------------------

        • Security groups (allow port 80/443)
        • Idle timeout
        • Access logs (store in S3)


    ==================================================
    TARGET GROUP – CONFIGURATION OPTIONS
    ==================================================

    --------------------------------------------------
    1) Target Type
    --------------------------------------------------

        • Instances (EC2 directly)
        • IP addresses (Microservices on ECS/EKS)
        • Lambda functions

    --------------------------------------------------
    2) Protocol & Port
    --------------------------------------------------

        • HTTP / HTTPS       (for ALB)
        • TCP / UDP / TLS    (for NLB)
        • Health check port
        • Traffic port

    --------------------------------------------------
    3) Health Checks
    --------------------------------------------------

        • Protocol (HTTP, HTTPS, TCP)
        • Health check path (for ALB)
              Example:  /health, /status
        • Success codes (200, 302, etc.)
        • Interval (default 30 seconds)
        • Healthy threshold
        • Unhealthy threshold
        • Timeout seconds

    --------------------------------------------------
    4) Advanced Health Check Features
    --------------------------------------------------

        • Deregistration delay
        • Slow start
        • Stickiness (session persistence)
        • Matcher codes
        • Health check override per target

    --------------------------------------------------
    5) Registered Targets
    --------------------------------------------------

        • Select EC2 Instances
        • Select IPs
        • Register Lambda functions


    --------------------------------------------------
    SUMMARY LINES
    --------------------------------------------------

        A load balancer distributes traffic across multiple servers
        to ensure availability, performance, and reliability.

        ALB works at Layer 7 for HTTP/HTTPS,
        NLB works at Layer 4 for fast TCP/UDP traffic,
        GWLB works at Layer 3 for firewall and security appliances.

        A target group is where the load balancer sends traffic.
        It defines health checks, ports, targets, and routing rules.
  


====================================================================
    WHAT IS USER DATA IN AWS?


        User Data is a script that runs automatically
        when an EC2 instance launches in

        It is used to automate initial server setup.

    --------------------------------------------------
    WHAT USER DATA CAN DO?
    --------------------------------------------------

        • Install software (Apache, Nginx, Java, Python)
        • Update packages
        • Create files or directories
        • Configure applications
        • Start services
        • Download code from GitHub/S3
        • Set environment variables

    --------------------------------------------------
    COMMON USER DATA SCRIPT (LINUX)
    --------------------------------------------------
#!/bin/bash

yum update -y
yum install -y httpd
systemctl enable httpd
systemctl start httpd
echo "THIS IS SAMPLE FACEBOOK PAGE" > /var/www/html/index.html

    --------------------------------------------------
    IMPORTANT POINTS
    --------------------------------------------------

        • Runs only on FIRST boot (unless configured otherwise)
        • Runs as root user
        • Stored in the EC2 instance metadata
        • Helps automate server provisioning


        User Data = "Auto-setup script" for your EC2.

        When the instance starts,
        AWS runs your script automatically,
        so you don't need to configure the server manually.




