====================================================================================================
13 FEB 2026


    AMAZON EFS (ELASTIC FILE SYSTEM) – SHORT NOTES

    1) WHAT IS NFS?
    --------------------------------------------------

        NFS = Network File System

        • A protocol used to share files over a network.
        • Allows multiple machines to access the same storage.
        • Works like a shared folder across servers.
        • Uses port 2049.

        Simple meaning:
            NFS is the technology that lets servers
            share files over the network.


    --------------------------------------------------
    WHAT IS EFS?
    --------------------------------------------------

        Amazon Elastic File System (EFS) is a
        fully managed, scalable file storage service in AWS.

        • It is shared file storage.
        • Multiple EC2 instances can access it at the same time.
        • Works using NFS protocol.
        • Automatically scales storage size.

        Simple meaning:
            EFS = Shared network drive for many servers.
		    EFS = AWS-managed NFS storage.
			
			        
		NFS → Protocol (technology) - 2049
        EFS → AWS service that uses NFS


    --------------------------------------------------
    WHERE IS EFS USED?
    --------------------------------------------------

        • Shared application data
        • Web servers needing same files
        • Container workloads (ECS, EKS)
        • Content management systems
        • Analytics workloads


    --------------------------------------------------
    HOW TO CONFIGURE EFS (SIMPLE STEPS)
    --------------------------------------------------

        1) Create EFS
              - Choose VPC
              - Select Availability Zones

        2) Create Mount Targets
              - One mount target per AZ
              - Attach security groups

        3) Configure Security Group
              - Allow NFS port 2049
              - Allow traffic from EC2 instances

        4) Launch EC2 in same VPC

        5) Mount EFS on EC2
              Example (Linux):
                  sudo mount -t nfs4 <efs-dns-name>:/ /mnt/efs

        6) Use it like a normal directory
              Files are shared across all mounted EC2s.


    --------------------------------------------------
    KEY FEATURES OF EFS
    --------------------------------------------------

        • Fully managed (no capacity planning)
        • Auto-scaling storage
        • Multi-AZ availability
        • Highly durable
        • Shared file access
        • Pay only for storage used


    --------------------------------------------------
    EFS VS EBS (IMPORTANT DIFFERENCE)
    --------------------------------------------------

        EBS (Elastic Block Store):

            • Block-level storage
            • Attached to ONE EC2 at a time
            • Like a hard disk
            • Must choose size manually
            • Typically used for OS / database storage

        EFS (Elastic File System):

            • File-level storage
            • Shared by multiple EC2s
            • Like a shared network folder
            • Auto-scales storage
            • Used for shared applications


    --------------------------------------------------
    SIMPLE COMPARISON
    --------------------------------------------------

        EBS  → Single server disk
        EFS  → Shared storage for many servers

        EBS  → Fixed size
        EFS  → Automatically grows

        EBS  → One instance at a time
        EFS  → Many instances simultaneously


    --------------------------------------------------
    WHEN TO USE WHICH?
    --------------------------------------------------

        Use EBS when:
            • You need storage for one EC2
            • You need high IOPS for database
            • You need boot volume

        Use EFS when:
            • Multiple EC2s need shared files
            • Applications need common storage
            • Containers need persistent shared storage


----------------------------------

        EFS = Managed, shared file storage in AWS.
        EBS = Block storage attached to a single EC2.

        EFS is for shared workloads.
        EBS is for individual server storage.
		
	


    --------------------------------------------------
    WHAT ARE EFS LIFECYCLE POLICIES?
    --------------------------------------------------

        EFS can automatically move files between
        storage classes to reduce cost.

        Based on how frequently files are accessed.


    --------------------------------------------------
    EFS STORAGE CLASSES
    --------------------------------------------------

        1) Standard
             • Frequently accessed files
             • Higher cost
             • High performance

        2) Infrequent Access (IA)
             • Files not accessed for 30+ days (configurable)
             • Lower storage cost
             • Small access charge

        3) Archive
             • Rarely accessed data
             • Very low cost
             • Higher access latency


    --------------------------------------------------
    HOW EFS LIFECYCLE POLICY WORKS
    --------------------------------------------------

        Example:

            File not accessed for 30 days
                → Automatically moves to IA

            File not accessed for 90 days
                → Moves to Archive

        If accessed again:
            It automatically moves back to Standard.


		
*************************************************************************************************************

    MOUNT TARGETS IN EFS – SHORT NOTES

    --------------------------------------------------
    WHAT IS A MOUNT TARGET?
    --------------------------------------------------

        A Mount Target is a network endpoint
        inside a subnet that allows EC2 instances
        to connect to EFS.

        It provides an IP address in your subnet
        for accessing EFS.


    --------------------------------------------------
    WHY DO WE NEED MOUNT TARGETS?
    --------------------------------------------------

        • EFS is a regional service (multi-AZ).
        • EC2 instances connect to EFS through
          mount targets.
        • Each Availability Zone needs its own
          mount target for high availability.


    --------------------------------------------------
    IMPORTANT RULE
    --------------------------------------------------

        One Mount Target per Availability Zone (AZ).

        Example:
            If your VPC has:
                AZ-a
                AZ-b
                AZ-c

            You should create:
                3 Mount Targets
                (one in each AZ)


    --------------------------------------------------
    HOW IT WORKS
    --------------------------------------------------

        EC2 Instance
             ↓
        Mount Target (in same AZ)
             ↓
        EFS File System


    --------------------------------------------------
    CONFIGURATION STEPS (SIMPLE)
    --------------------------------------------------

        1) Create EFS
        2) Select VPC
        3) Choose subnets (one per AZ)
        4) Attach security group
              - Allow NFS port 2049
        5) EC2 mounts EFS using DNS name


    --------------------------------------------------
    SECURITY REQUIREMENT
    --------------------------------------------------

        Security Group must allow:

            Port 2049 (NFS)
            Source = EC2 Security Group


    --------------------------------------------------
    SIMPLE SUMMARY
    --------------------------------------------------

        Mount Target = Access point to EFS
        Lives inside a subnet
        One per AZ
        Required for EC2 to connect to EFS
        Uses NFS protocol (port 2049)



--------------------------------------------------------------------

 WHAT IS A MOUNT TARGET?
    --------------------------------------------------

        A Mount Target is a network endpoint
        inside a subnet that allows EC2 instances
        to connect to EFS.

   

