    IAM –  NOTES

    --------------------------------------------------
    AUTHENTICATION VS AUTHORIZATION
    --------------------------------------------------

        Authentication:
            Verifying WHO you are.
            Example:
                - Username + Password
                - Access Key + Secret Key
                - MFA

        Authorization:
            Deciding WHAT you are allowed to do.
            Example:
                - Can you create EC2?
                - Can you delete S3 bucket?
                - Can you access RDS?

        Simple meaning:
            Authentication → Identity check
            Authorization  → Permission check


    --------------------------------------------------
    WHAT IS IAM?
    --------------------------------------------------

        IAM = Identity and Access Management.

        IAM is a service in Amazon Web Services (AWS)
        that controls:

            • Who can access AWS (Authentication)
            • What they can do (Authorization)

        It manages users, groups, roles, and policies.


    --------------------------------------------------
    WHAT IS AN IAM USER?
    --------------------------------------------------

        An IAM User represents a person or application
        that needs access to AWS.

        It can have:
            • Console password
            • Access keys (for CLI/API)

        Example:
            - Developer
            - DevOps engineer
            - Automation script


    --------------------------------------------------
    WHAT IS AN IAM POLICY?
    --------------------------------------------------

        An IAM Policy is a JSON document
        that defines permissions.

        It controls:
            • Allowed actions
            • Denied actions
            • Specific resources
            • Optional conditions

        Example:
            Allow:
                ec2:StartInstances
                ec2:StopInstances


    --------------------------------------------------
    WHAT IS A CUSTOM POLICY?
    --------------------------------------------------

        Custom Policy = A policy created by you.

        Used when AWS managed policies
        do not meet your exact requirement.

        Gives fine-grained control.
		
		
		

    --------------------------------------------------
    BASIC STRUCTURE OF A POLICY
    --------------------------------------------------

        {
          "Version": "2012-10-17",
          "Statement": [
            {
              "Effect": "Allow",
              "Action": "ec2:StartInstances",
              "Resource": "*"
            }
          ]
        }


    --------------------------------------------------
    IMPORTANT KEYWORDS EXPLAINED
    --------------------------------------------------

    1) Version
        • Defines policy language version.
        • Usually: "2012-10-17"

    2) Statement
        • Main block containing permission rules.
        • A policy can have multiple statements.

    3) Effect
        • Defines whether access is allowed or denied.
        • Values:
              - "Allow"
              - "Deny"

        Example:
            "Effect": "Allow"

    4) Action
        • Defines what operation is permitted.
        • Format:
              service:operation

        Examples:
              ec2:StartInstances
              s3:PutObject
              iam:CreateUser

    5) Resource
        • Defines on which AWS resource
          the action is allowed.

        Example:
              "*" → All resources
              Specific EC2 ARN
              Specific S3 bucket ARN


    --------------------------------------------------
    OPTIONAL: CONDITION (ADVANCED)
    --------------------------------------------------

        You can add conditions like:

            • Allow only from specific IP
            • Allow only during certain time
            • Allow only if MFA is enabled


    --------------------------------------------------
    SIMPLE MEANING
    --------------------------------------------------

        Effect   → Allow or Deny
        Action   → What operation
        Resource → On which resource

        In simple words:

            "Allow this action on this resource."



    --------------------------------------------------
    WHAT IS AN IAM GROUP?
    --------------------------------------------------

        An IAM Group is a collection of IAM users.

        You attach a policy to the group,
        and all users inside inherit permissions.

        Example:
            Group: Developers → S3 Read Only
            Group: Admins → Full Access


    --------------------------------------------------
    SIMPLE SUMMARY
    --------------------------------------------------

        Authentication → Verify identity
        Authorization  → Grant permissions

        IAM        → Access control system
        IAM User   → Individual identity
        IAM Policy → Permission rules
        IAM Group  → Collection of users
        Custom Policy → User-defined permission rules


************************************************************************************************


DATE: 16 FEB 2026




    AMAZON S3 – COMPLETE NOTES (FINAL UPDATED)

    --------------------------------------------------
    WHAT IS S3?
    --------------------------------------------------

        S3 = Simple Storage Service.

        It is an object storage service in Amazon Web Services (AWS).

        • Stores data as objects
        • Highly durable (11 9’s durability)
        • Infinitely scalable
        • Accessible over HTTP/HTTPS
        • No server management required


    --------------------------------------------------
    BASIC TERMINOLOGY
    --------------------------------------------------

        Bucket:
            Container that stores objects.
            Bucket name must be globally unique.

        Object:
            File stored in S3 (data + metadata + key).

        Key:
            Unique name of the object inside bucket.

        Region:
            Bucket is created in a specific AWS region.


    --------------------------------------------------
    S3 VERSIONING
    --------------------------------------------------

        Versioning allows multiple versions
        of the same object.

        • Protects from accidental delete
        • Protects from accidental overwrite
        • Each upload creates new Version ID

        States:
            - Enabled
            - Suspended
            - Never enabled


    --------------------------------------------------
    DELETE MARKER
    --------------------------------------------------

        When versioning is enabled:

            Deleting an object creates
            a "Delete Marker".

        • Object appears deleted
        • Old versions still exist
        • Can restore by removing delete marker


    --------------------------------------------------
    S3 LIFECYCLE POLICY
    --------------------------------------------------

        Automatically moves or deletes objects
        based on time rules.

        Example:

            After 30 days → Standard-IA
            After 90 days → Glacier
            After 365 days → Delete

        Used for cost optimization.


    --------------------------------------------------
    WHAT IS A STATIC WEBSITE?
    --------------------------------------------------

        A static website contains only:

            • HTML
            • CSS
            • JavaScript
            • Images

        No backend processing.
        No database.
        No server-side logic.

        Example:
            Portfolio website
            Landing page
            Company info page


    --------------------------------------------------
    HOW TO HOST STATIC WEBSITE IN S3
    --------------------------------------------------

        Step 1:
            Create an S3 bucket
            (Bucket name = domain name recommended)

        Step 2:
            Upload:
                - index.html
                - error.html
                - CSS, JS files

        Step 3:
            Enable "Static Website Hosting"
                • Set index document
                • Set error document

        Step 4:
            Update Bucket Policy
                Allow public read access

        Step 5:
            Use generated S3 website URL

        Optional:
            Use CloudFront for HTTPS + CDN


    --------------------------------------------------
    WHY STATIC WEBSITE IS GOOD FOR S3?
    --------------------------------------------------

        • No server required
        • No EC2 cost
        • Highly scalable
        • Very low cost
        • High availability
        • Easy deployment
        • Integrated with CloudFront CDN

        Perfect for:
            - React apps
            - Angular apps
            - Documentation sites
            - Landing pages


    --------------------------------------------------
    S3 STORAGE CLASSES
    --------------------------------------------------

        • Standard
        • Standard-IA
        • One Zone-IA
        • Intelligent Tiering
        • Glacier
        • Deep Archive


    --------------------------------------------------
    S3 FEATURES
    --------------------------------------------------

        • High durability
        • Versioning
        • Lifecycle policies
        • Encryption
        • Replication
        • Event notifications
        • Static website hosting
        • Access control


    --------------------------------------------------
    REAL-TIME USE CASES
    --------------------------------------------------

        • Backups
        • Log storage
        • Media storage
        • CI/CD artifacts
        • Data lake
        • Static website hosting


    --------------------------------------------------
    S3 VS EBS VS EFS
    --------------------------------------------------

        S3  → Object storage (HTTP based)
        EBS → Block storage (attached disk)
        EFS → Shared file storage (NFS based)


    --------------------------------------------------
    SIMPLE SUMMARY
    --------------------------------------------------

        S3 = Scalable object storage
        Versioning = Keeps multiple copies
        Delete Marker = Hides object on delete
        Lifecycle = Auto move/delete
        Static Hosting = Host HTML websites without servers

        S3 is best for scalable, durable,
        low-cost storage and static websites.


-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    REAL DEVOPS PROJECT USING S3

    --------------------------------------------------
    PROJECT 1: STATIC WEBSITE + CI/CD PIPELINE
    --------------------------------------------------

        Use Case:
            Deploy a React/Angular static website automatically.

        Architecture:
            Developer pushes code → GitHub
            CI/CD Pipeline builds app
            Build output uploaded to S3 bucket
            CloudFront serves website globally

        Steps:

            1) Create S3 bucket
                   Enable static website hosting
                   Upload index.html

            2) Create CloudFront distribution
                   Set S3 as origin

            3) Setup CI/CD (GitHub Actions / Jenkins)
                   - Build project
                   - Upload build folder to S3
                   - Invalidate CloudFront cache

        Why S3?
            • No EC2 required
            • Auto scaling
            • Very low cost
            • Highly available


    --------------------------------------------------
    PROJECT 2: LOG STORAGE + MONITORING
    --------------------------------------------------

        Use Case:
            Store application logs securely.

        Architecture:
            EC2 / Containers generate logs
            Logs pushed to S3
            Athena used for querying
            CloudWatch alerts on errors

        Why S3?
            • Cheap long-term storage
            • Lifecycle rules to move to Glacier
            • Durable storage


    --------------------------------------------------
    PROJECT 3: BACKUP & DISASTER RECOVERY
    --------------------------------------------------

        Use Case:
            Backup EBS snapshots or database dumps.

        Flow:
            RDS snapshot / DB dump
                ↓
            Stored in S3
                ↓
            Replicated to another region

        Benefits:
            • Cross-region replication
            • Versioning protects backups
            • Lifecycle reduces cost


    --------------------------------------------------
    PROJECT 4: TERRAFORM REMOTE STATE STORAGE
    --------------------------------------------------

        Use Case:
            Store Terraform state file securely.

        Setup:
            Create S3 bucket
            Enable versioning
            Enable encryption
            Use DynamoDB for locking

        Benefit:
            • Team collaboration
            • State file safety
            • Prevent corruption


    --------------------------------------------------
    PROJECT 5: CI/CD ARTIFACT STORAGE
    --------------------------------------------------

        Use Case:
            Store build artifacts (JAR, WAR, Docker layers)

        Flow:
            Code build → Artifact generated
            Artifact uploaded to S3
            Deployment server downloads artifact

        Why?
            • Central storage
            • Secure
            • Easy integration


    --------------------------------------------------
    WHY S3 IS PERFECT FOR DEVOPS
    --------------------------------------------------

        • Highly scalable
        • Cost-effective
        • No infrastructure management
        • Easy integration with:
              - EC2
              - Lambda
              - CloudFront
              - Athena
              - Glue
              - CI/CD tools

        • Supports automation via CLI and SDK


    --------------------------------------------------
    SIMPLE SUMMARY
    --------------------------------------------------

        In DevOps, S3 is used for:

            • Static website hosting
            • Backup storage
            • Log storage
            • Terraform state
            • Artifact repository
            • Data lake storage

        S3 is one of the most used AWS services
        in real-world DevOps projects.

========================================================

    AWS S3 STORAGE CLASSES – SHORT NOTES

    (Inside Amazon Web Services (AWS))


    --------------------------------------------------
    1) S3 STANDARD
    --------------------------------------------------

        • Frequently accessed data
        • High availability
        • Low latency
        • Higher storage cost

        Use When:
            - Active websites
            - Applications
            - Frequently used files


    --------------------------------------------------
    2) S3 STANDARD – INFREQUENT ACCESS (STANDARD-IA)
    --------------------------------------------------

        • Rarely accessed data
        • Lower storage cost
        • Small retrieval fee

        Use When:
            - Backups
            - Disaster recovery copies
            - Data accessed occasionally


    --------------------------------------------------
    3) S3 ONE ZONE-IA
    --------------------------------------------------

        • Stored in single Availability Zone
        • Lower cost than Standard-IA
        • Less resilient

        Use When:
            - Secondary backups
            - Re-creatable data
            - Non-critical data


    --------------------------------------------------
    4) S3 INTELLIGENT-TIERING
    --------------------------------------------------

        • Automatically moves data
          between frequent and infrequent tiers
        • Slight monitoring fee

        Use When:
            - Access pattern is unpredictable
            - You don’t want to manage lifecycle rules


    --------------------------------------------------
    5) S3 GLACIER INSTANT RETRIEVAL
    --------------------------------------------------

        • Archival data
        • Immediate retrieval
        • Lower cost than Standard

        Use When:
            - Archived but occasionally needed data
            - Compliance documents


    --------------------------------------------------
    6) S3 GLACIER FLEXIBLE RETRIEVAL
    --------------------------------------------------

        • Very low storage cost
        • Retrieval takes minutes to hours

        Use When:
            - Long-term backups
            - Rarely accessed archives


    --------------------------------------------------
    7) S3 GLACIER DEEP ARCHIVE
    --------------------------------------------------

        • Lowest storage cost
        • Retrieval takes hours
        • Designed for long-term retention (7+ years)

        Use When:
            - Legal/compliance storage
            - Old audit data
            - Rarely accessed historical data


    --------------------------------------------------
    SIMPLE DECISION GUIDE
    --------------------------------------------------

        Frequent access      → Standard
        Rare access          → Standard-IA
        Single AZ + cheaper  → One Zone-IA
        Unknown pattern      → Intelligent-Tiering
        Archive + fast read  → Glacier Instant
        Archive + low cost   → Glacier Flexible
        Very long-term       → Glacier Deep Archive


    --------------------------------------------------
    SIMPLE SUMMARY
    --------------------------------------------------

        Standard = Active data  
        IA = Less frequently used data  
        Glacier = Archive data  
        Intelligent-Tiering = Auto optimization  

