DATE: 17 FEB 2026

    AWS CLI – COMPLETE SHORT NOTES

    --------------------------------------------------
    WHAT IS AWS CLI?
    --------------------------------------------------

        AWS CLI = Command Line Interface.

        It is a tool that allows you to interact with
        Amazon Web Services (AWS) using commands
        from terminal instead of the web console (GUI).

        Example:
            aws s3 ls
            aws ec2 describe-instances


    --------------------------------------------------
    WHY DO WE NEED AWS CLI WHEN GUI EXISTS?
    --------------------------------------------------

        GUI:
            • Good for beginners
            • Manual operations
            • Not automation-friendly

        AWS CLI:
            • Faster
            • Scriptable
            • Automatable
            • Used in CI/CD pipelines
            • Used in production troubleshooting
            • Works in servers without browser

        DevOps rule:
            If you repeat a task → Automate it.
            CLI helps automation.

AKIA5Wxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx
elFDCxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx


    --------------------------------------------------
    HOW AWS CLI WORKS
    --------------------------------------------------

        1) Install AWS CLI
        2) Configure credentials:

            aws configure

            Enter:
                Access Key
                Secret Key
                Region
                Output format -- none / json 

        Credentials are stored locally ( in user home directly 

    --------------------------------------------------
    BASIC COMMAND STRUCTURE
    --------------------------------------------------

        aws <service> <operation> --parameters

        Example:
            aws ec2 describe-instances
            aws s3 cp file.txt s3://mybucket/


    --------------------------------------------------
    DAY-TO-DAY DEVOPS OPERATIONS USING AWS CLI
    --------------------------------------------------

    1) S3 OPERATIONS

        List buckets:
            aws s3 ls

        List files inside bucket:
            aws s3 ls s3://mybucket/

        Upload file:
            aws s3 cp file.txt s3://mybucket/

        Download file:
            aws s3 cp s3://mybucket/file.txt .

        Sync local folder:
            aws s3 sync ./app s3://mybucket/


    2) EC2 OPERATIONS

        List EC2 instances:
            aws ec2 describe-instances

        Start instance:
            aws ec2 start-instances --instance-ids i-0a54fdb26081aade5

        Stop instance:
            aws ec2 stop-instances --instance-ids i-123456

        Terminate instance:
            aws ec2 terminate-instances --instance-ids i-123456
			
	
        TO create instance

aws ec2 run-instances \
  --image-id ami-0c1fe732b5494dc14 \
  --instance-type t3.micro \
  --key-name batch17a \
  --tag-specifications 'ResourceType=instance,Tags=[{Key=Name,Value=Dev-Server},{Key=Env,Value=Dev}]'



	


    3) SECURITY GROUP OPERATIONS

        List security groups:
            aws ec2 describe-security-groups

        Authorize inbound rule:
            aws ec2 authorize-security-group-ingress \
                --group-id sg-12345 \
                --protocol tcp \
                --port 22 \
                --cidr 0.0.0.0/0


    4) IAM OPERATIONS

        List IAM users:
            aws iam list-users

        Create IAM user:
            aws iam create-user --user-name devuser

        Attach policy:
            aws iam attach-user-policy \
                --user-name devuser \
                --policy-arn arn:aws:iam::aws:policy/AmazonS3ReadOnlyAccess


    5) CLOUDWATCH LOGS

        Describe log groups:
            aws logs describe-log-groups


    6) AUTO SCALING

        Describe ASGs:
            aws autoscaling describe-auto-scaling-groups


    --------------------------------------------------
    REAL DEVOPS USE CASES
    --------------------------------------------------

        • Automate deployments
        • Upload build artifacts to S3
        • Trigger infrastructure changes
        • Backup automation scripts
        • Monitoring and log retrieval
        • Managing EC2 fleet
        • Managing IAM users programmatically
        • Used inside:
              - Jenkins
              - GitHub Actions
              - Terraform external scripts


    --------------------------------------------------
    WHY CLI IS VERY IMPORTANT FOR DEVOPS
    --------------------------------------------------

        • Infrastructure as Code relies on CLI
        • Automation requires CLI
        • GUI is not scalable
        • Production servers don’t have browsers
        • Faster troubleshooting


    --------------------------------------------------
    SIMPLE SUMMARY
    --------------------------------------------------

        AWS CLI = Terminal-based access to AWS.

        GUI = Manual work
        CLI = Automation + Speed + DevOps

        Every DevOps engineer must know AWS CLI.


18 FEB 2026

    IAM ROLE 

    --------------------------------------------------
    WHAT IS AN IAM ROLE?
    --------------------------------------------------

An IAM role is an identity you can create that has specific permissions with credentials that are valid for short durations. Roles can be assumed by entities that you trust.


        An IAM Role is an AWS identity
        that has permissions but does NOT have
        permanent credentials (no username/password).

        A role is assumed temporarily
        by a user, application, or AWS service.


    --------------------------------------------------
    SIMPLE DEFINITION
    --------------------------------------------------

        IAM User  → Permanent identity (person or app)
        IAM Role  → Temporary identity (assumed when needed)


    --------------------------------------------------
    IAM USER VS IAM ROLE
    --------------------------------------------------

        IAM User:
            • Has username
            • Has password
            • Has access keys
            • Long-term credentials
            • Used for people or external apps

        IAM Role:
            • No password
            • No permanent access keys
            • Temporary security credentials
            • Automatically rotated credentials
            • Used by AWS services or cross-account access


    --------------------------------------------------
    WHY IAM ROLE IS IMPORTANT?
    --------------------------------------------------

        • More secure (no hardcoded access keys)
        • Temporary credentials
        • Automatically rotated
        • Best practice in production
        • Required for service-to-service access


    --------------------------------------------------
    REAL-TIME USE CASES
    --------------------------------------------------

    1) EC2 ACCESSING S3

        Scenario:
            EC2 needs to upload logs to S3.

        Wrong Way:
            Store access key inside EC2 (unsafe).

        Correct Way:
            Attach IAM Role to EC2.
            EC2 automatically gets temporary credentials.

        Benefit:
            No secret keys stored on server.


    --------------------------------------------------

    2) LAMBDA ACCESSING DYNAMODB

        Lambda function needs database access.

        Solution:
            Attach IAM Role to Lambda
            with required DynamoDB permissions.


    --------------------------------------------------

    3) CROSS-ACCOUNT ACCESS

        Company has:
            Account A (Dev)
            Account B (Prod)

        Dev engineers assume a role
        in Production account temporarily.


    --------------------------------------------------

    4) CI/CD PIPELINE ACCESS

        Jenkins / GitHub Actions
        assumes an IAM Role to:

            • Deploy EC2
            • Upload artifacts to S3
            • Modify infrastructure


    --------------------------------------------------

    5) EKS / ECS SERVICE ROLES

        Containers need access to:
            • S3
            • Secrets Manager
            • RDS

        IAM Role provides temporary secure access.


    --------------------------------------------------
    HOW IAM ROLE WORKS (SIMPLE FLOW)
    --------------------------------------------------

        User / Service
                ↓
        Assumes Role
                ↓
        Gets Temporary Credentials
                ↓
        Performs allowed actions


    --------------------------------------------------
    IMPORTANT TERMS
    --------------------------------------------------

        Trust Policy:
            Defines WHO can assume the role.
			
			
			
	    {
    "Version": "2012-10-17",
    "Statement": [
        {
            "Effect": "Allow",
            "Action": [
                "sts:AssumeRole"
            ],
            "Principal": {
                "Service": [
                    "ec2.amazonaws.com"
                ]
            }
        }
    ]
    }		
			
			

        Permission Policy:
            Defines WHAT actions are allowed.


    --------------------------------------------------
    SIMPLE SUMMARY
    --------------------------------------------------

        IAM User  → Permanent login identity
        IAM Role  → Temporary permission identity

        Role is safer and preferred
        for applications and AWS services.

        DevOps best practice:
            Always use IAM Role instead of storing access keys.


===============================================================


====================================================================
====================================================================
RDS & DATABASE TYPES
====================================================================


DATABASE SERVICES IN AWS
------------------------

AWS provides database services under Amazon RDS
(Relational Database Service) and other NoSQL services.


====================================================================
1) STRUCTURED DATABASES (RELATIONAL DATABASES)
====================================================================

Definition:

    Structured databases store data in predefined schemas.
    Data is organized into tables with rows and columns.

    They use SQL (Structured Query Language)
    to query and manage data.

Key Characteristics:

    • Fixed schema
    • Tables, rows, columns
    • Relationships using foreign keys
    • ACID compliant (transactions)
    • Strong consistency


Examples:

MySQL
    Open-source RDBMS.
    Commonly used for web applications.

PostgreSQL
    Advanced open-source RDBMS.
    Supports complex queries and extensions.

Microsoft SQL Server
    Enterprise database by Microsoft.
    Strong integration with .NET ecosystem.

Oracle Database
    Enterprise-grade commercial database.
    High scalability and performance.

IBM Db2
    Enterprise RDBMS optimized for large workloads.

SQLite
    Lightweight embedded relational database.
    Used in mobile and desktop apps.


AWS RELATIONAL SERVICE:

    Amazon RDS supports:
        - MySQL
        - PostgreSQL
        - MariaDB
        - SQL Server
        - Oracle

    Amazon Aurora
        AWS-optimized high-performance relational database.


CRUD 

====================================================================
2) SEMI-STRUCTURED DATABASES (NoSQL – Flexible Schema)
====================================================================

Definition:

    Semi-structured databases do not require fixed schema.
    Data structure can vary between records.

    Often use:
        - JSON
        - Key-value
        - Wide-column format

Key Characteristics:

    • Flexible schema
    • Horizontally scalable
    • High availability
    • Suitable for large-scale distributed systems


Examples:

MongoDB
    Document database storing JSON-like documents.

Apache Cassandra
    Distributed wide-column database.
    Designed for high scalability.

Amazon DynamoDB
    Fully managed NoSQL key-value database by AWS.

Google Cloud Datastore
    Document-based NoSQL database.

OrientDB
    Multi-model database (graph + document).


AWS NoSQL Services:

    DynamoDB
    DocumentDB (MongoDB compatible)


====================================================================
3) UNSTRUCTURED DATA (NOT A DATABASE TYPE)
====================================================================

Important note:

    Unstructured data is NOT equal to NoSQL database.

    Unstructured data means:
        Data without fixed format or schema.

Examples of Unstructured Data:

    • Images
    • Videos
    • Audio
    • Log files
    • PDFs
    • Backups


Tools Used to Store Unstructured Data:

Amazon S3
    Object storage for unlimited unstructured data.

Azure Blob Storage
    Object storage for binary data.

Hadoop (HDFS)
    Distributed file system for big data.

Elasticsearch
    Search engine for logs and text indexing.

Apache Solr
    Text search engine built on Lucene.

Cassandra (with blobs)
    Can store binary data, but not ideal for large files.


Important Note:

    Object storage like S3 is NOT a database.
    It is storage service.


====================================================================
SIMPLE COMPARISON
====================================================================

Structured
    Fixed schema
    SQL based
    Strong consistency
    Example: MySQL, PostgreSQL

Semi-Structured (NoSQL)
    Flexible schema
    JSON / key-value
    Highly scalable
    Example: MongoDB, DynamoDB

Unstructured
    No defined format
    Stored in object storage
    Example: Images in S3


====================================================================
WHEN TO USE WHAT?
====================================================================

Use Relational DB:
    - Banking systems
    - ERP systems
    - Transactions
    - Strong consistency required

Use NoSQL:
    - Large-scale web apps
    - Real-time apps
    - IoT data
    - High traffic apps

Use Object Storage (S3):
    - Media storage
    - Backups
    - Logs
    - Data lakes


====================================================================
AWS DATABASE SUMMARY
====================================================================

Relational:
    Amazon RDS
    Amazon Aurora

NoSQL:
    DynamoDB
    DocumentDB

In-memory:
    ElastiCache (Redis, Memcached)

Search:
    OpenSearch (Elasticsearch service)

Object Storage:
    Amazon S3





