DATE: 23 FEB 2026

    AWS ROUTE 53 – DETAILED NOTES WITH REAL-TIME EXAMPLE

    --------------------------------------------------
    WHAT IS ROUTE 53?
    --------------------------------------------------

        Amazon Route 53 is a scalable and highly available
        **DNS (Domain Name System)** service provided by AWS.

        DNS = Converts domain names into IP addresses.

        Example:
            You type: www.myapp.com
            DNS converts it to → 54.23.10.8 (server IP)

        Route 53 helps:
            • Register domain names
            • Host DNS records
            • Route traffic to applications
            • Health-check endpoints


    --------------------------------------------------
    WHY THE NAME "ROUTE 53"?
    --------------------------------------------------

        53 = DNS uses port number 53 (UDP/TCP).


    --------------------------------------------------
    WHAT CAN ROUTE 53 DO?
    --------------------------------------------------

        1) Domain Registration
             Buy domains (example: myapp.com)

        2) DNS Hosting
             Create DNS records like A, CNAME, MX, TXT

        3) Route Traffic
             Send users to:
                • EC2
                • Load Balancers
                • S3 static websites
                • CloudFront
                • External servers

        4) Health Checks
             Detect unhealthy servers and reroute traffic

        5) Traffic Routing Policies
             Distribute traffic based on business needs


    --------------------------------------------------
    COMMON DNS RECORD TYPES IN ROUTE 53
    --------------------------------------------------

        A Record
            Domain → IPv4 address
            Example: myapp.com → 54.10.20.30

        AAAA Record
            Domain → IPv6 address

        CNAME
            Alias → Another domain
            Example: api.myapp.com → backend.myapp.com

        Alias Record
            AWS-specific record type
            Example: myapp.com → ALB / CloudFront / S3

        MX Record
            Mail servers

        TXT Record
            Verification (DKIM, SPF, Google verification)


    --------------------------------------------------
    ROUTING POLICIES
    --------------------------------------------------

        1) Simple Routing
            One domain → one endpoint

        2) Weighted Routing
            Split traffic (ex: 70% v1, 30% v2)

        3) Latency-Based Routing
            User routed to nearest region

        4) Failover Routing
            Primary active → Backup only when primary fails

        5) Geo Location Routing
            Route based on user country

        6) Geo Proximity Routing
            Region-based routing with bias control

        7) Multi-Value Answer
            Return multiple healthy IPs


    --------------------------------------------------
    REAL-TIME EXAMPLE
    --------------------------------------------------

    Scenario:
        You have a production website hosted in AWS.

        Architecture:
            - ALB (Application Load Balancer)
            - EC2 instances behind ALB
            - Domain name purchased: myapp.com

    Steps:

        1) Buy domain in Route 53
               myapp.com

        2) Create Hosted Zone
               Auto-created when buying the domain

        3) Create DNS Record
               A or Alias record:
                   myapp.com → ALB DNS name

               Example:
                   myapp.com → myapp-alb-123.amazonaws.com

        4) User accesses website
               User types myapp.com
                     ↓
               Route 53 resolves domain
                     ↓
               Points to ALB
                     ↓
               ALB forwards to EC2 backend servers

        5) Health Check (optional)
               Route 53 monitors EC2 or ALB health
               If instance is unhealthy → traffic moved away


    --------------------------------------------------
    WHY ROUTE 53 IS IMPORTANT FOR DEVOPS?
    --------------------------------------------------

        • Used in almost every real-time application
        • Needed for domain → application mapping
        • Used with:
            - S3 static websites
            - CloudFront
            - ALB/NLB
            - Multi-region deployments
            - Disaster recovery setups


    --------------------------------------------------
    SIMPLE SUMMARY
    --------------------------------------------------

        Route 53 = DNS + Traffic Routing + Domain registration.

        It converts domain names into IP addresses
        and routes users to the correct AWS resource.

        Essential for hosting websites & APIs in AWS.
